  "text": "The Rust compiler's trait obligation chain is a multi-stage process that fulfills trait predicates through a forest-based data structure and selection algorithm. Here's how trait obligations are resolved:\n\n## 1. ObligationForest - Core Data Structure\nThe foundation of the trait obligation system is the `ObligationForest` (compiler/rustc_data_structures/src/obligation_forest/mod.rs). This utility data structure tracks outstanding trait obligations that haven't yet been resolved. Obligations form a tree structure where each obligation can have sub-obligations. The forest processes obligations and returns outcomes with completed obligations and errors.\n\nThe `ObligationForest` uses a generic `ForestObligation` trait to allow different obligation types. `PendingPredicateObligation` is the concrete implementation used in trait selection, defined in compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/fulfill.rs.\n\n## 2. FulfillmentContext - Orchestrating Obligation Resolution\nThe `FulfillmentContext` (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/fulfill.rs) drives the trait resolution process. It wraps an `ObligationForest<PendingPredicateObligation>` and provides methods to:\n- Register new root obligations\n- Process obligations through the forest\n- Return fulfillment errors for unsatisfied obligations\n\nDuring the fulfillment process, the `FulfillProcessor` (a struct implementing `ObligationProcessor`) works with a `SelectionContext` to process each obligation.\n\n## 3. Trait Selection - SelectionContext\nThe `SelectionContext` (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/mod.rs) is responsible for determining whether a trait obligation can be satisfied. It orchestrates the entire selection process with the following steps:\n\n### 3a. Candidate Assembly (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/candidate_assembly.rs)\nThe `assemble_candidates` method collects all possible candidates that could satisfy a trait obligation:\n- `assemble_candidates_from_impls` - searches for matching trait impls in the codebase\n- `assemble_candidates_from_caller_bounds` - checks where-clause bounds\n- `assemble_builtin_copy_clone_candidate` - for builtin traits like Copy and Clone\n- Other specialized candidate assembly methods for specific lang items\n\n### 3b. Impl Matching (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/_match.rs)\nThe `MatchAgainstFreshVars` struct implements matching logic that tests whether an impl header can be unified with the obligation. Matching involves:\n- Replacing bound regions in the obligation with placeholders\n- Unifying the impl header with the obligation\n- Checking for placeholder leaks (where placeholders relate to non-impl regions)\n\n### 3c. Candidate Confirmation (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/confirmation.rs)\nOnce a candidate is selected, `confirm_candidate` confirms it and returns:\n- The impl source (UserDefined, Builtin, etc.)\n- Any nested obligations required by the impl\n\n## 4. Error Reporting - Unsatisfied Trait Bounds\nWhen trait obligations cannot be satisfied, error reporting occurs through:\n\n### 4a. Error Types (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/mod.rs)\n`FulfillmentError` combines:\n- The obligation that failed\n- `FulfillmentErrorCode` which can be:\n  - `Select(SelectionError)` - trait selection failed (Unimplemented is primary error)\n  - `Project(MismatchedProjectionTypes)` - associated type mismatch\n  - `Ambiguity` - multiple possible solutions\n\n### 4b. Error Reporting Pipeline (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/error_reporting/traits/fulfillment_errors.rs)\nThe `report_selection_error` method handles different error scenarios:\n- For `SelectionError::Unimplemented` - trait not implemented for the type\n- Provides specific context from well-formedness checking\n- Generates helpful suggestions for common mistakes\n\n### 4c. Main Error Reporter (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/error_reporting/traits/mod.rs)\nThe `report_fulfillment_errors` method in `TypeErrCtxt` is the entry point for reporting all trait bound errors. It processes multiple errors and coordinates with suggestion providers to give users helpful guidance.\n\n## End-to-End Flow\n1. Obligations are registered in `FulfillmentContext`\n2. `process_obligations` is called on the `ObligationForest`\n3. `FulfillProcessor` works with `SelectionContext` for each obligation\n4. `assemble_candidates` collects all possible trait impl matches\n5. `MatchAgainstFreshVars` determines if impls match the obligation\n6. Successful matches are confirmed, returning nested obligations\n7. Unfulfillable obligations become errors\n8. `report_fulfillment_errors` generates user-facing error messages with suggestions\n\nThis architecture ensures efficient trait obligation resolution while providing detailed error messages when traits cannot be satisfied."
}

